<group name="soc-lab,custom-detections">

<!--
  ╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
  ║  HOW WAZUH RULES WORK — QUICK REFERENCE                                     ║
  ║                                                                              ║
  ║  <rule id="X" level="Y">                                                     ║
  ║    id     : Unique integer. Custom rules must use 100000–199999.             ║
  ║    level  : 0–15 alert severity.                                             ║
  ║              0–2  = system/debug   (not usually alerted)                    ║
  ║              3–5  = low            (informational)                           ║
  ║              6–9  = medium         (worth reviewing)                         ║
  ║              10–12 = high          (investigate promptly)                    ║
  ║              13–14 = critical      (immediate response)                      ║
  ║              15   = maximum        (fire everything, wake people up)         ║
  ║                                                                              ║
  ║  <if_matched_sid>  : Fires when another rule has ALREADY fired N times      ║
  ║  <if_sid>          : Fires when another rule fires in the same event         ║
  ║  <if_group>        : Fires when event belongs to a group                     ║
  ║  <field name="X">  : Matches a decoded field value (supports regex)          ║
  ║  <same_source_ip>  : Counts only events from the SAME source IP              ║
  ║  <frequency>       : How many times rule must match within <timeframe>       ║
  ║  <timeframe>       : Sliding window in seconds for frequency counting        ║
  ║  <mitre>           : ATT&CK technique IDs for dashboard/reporting            ║
  ║  <group>           : Logical tags — used for filtering and dashboard views   ║
  ╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝
-->


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100001 — SSH Brute Force Detection
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Counts the number of times Wazuh built-in rule 5760 fires from the
         same source IP within a sliding 60-second window. Rule 5760 is the
         standard "sshd: authentication failed" rule that ships with Wazuh.
         When the count reaches 10, this rule fires at level 12 (High).

       WHY THESE THRESHOLDS:
         - frequency="10": 10 failures in 60s is aggressive enough to be an
           automated attack. Legitimate users who mistype their password rarely
           exceed 3 attempts. Setting this too low (e.g. 3) causes many false
           positives from users with password managers that auto-retry.
         - timeframe="60": A 60-second window is tight enough to catch real-time
           brute force tools (Hydra, Medusa) while ignoring slow distributed
           attacks that pace themselves at 1 attempt per minute.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         Increase frequency to 20 if you see many false positives from:
           - CI/CD systems doing frequent SSH-based deployments
           - Monitoring tools that test SSH connectivity
           - Users with many SSH keys causing auth failures before the right one
         Decrease timeframe to 30 if you want to catch faster tooling.
         Increase timeframe to 120 to catch slower distributed attacks.

       FALSE POSITIVE SOURCES:
         - Port scanners that probe SSH with no intent to auth
         - Misconfigured automation using wrong credentials
         - Shodan/Censys internet scanning (check IP reputation first)

       RESPONSE: Open TheHive case using brute-force-case-template.json
                 Block IP with UFW/iptables if not RFC1918
                 Escalate if rule 100002 fires within 120s
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100001" level="12" frequency="10" timeframe="60">

    <!-- Parent rule: triggers when built-in SSH failure rule fires 10x -->
    <if_matched_sid>5760</if_matched_sid>

    <!-- Count per source IP — don't mix attackers together -->
    <same_source_ip />

    <!-- Human-readable description — appears in Wazuh/Kibana dashboards -->
    <!-- $(srcip) is a dynamic substitution of the decoded source IP field -->
    <description>SSH brute force attack: 10+ failed logins from $(srcip) in 60 seconds</description>

    <!-- MITRE ATT&CK mapping for the Wazuh MITRE dashboard -->
    <mitre>
      <id>T1110.001</id>   <!-- Brute Force: Password Guessing -->
    </mitre>

    <!-- Groups used for filtering in dashboards and integration routing -->
    <!-- pci_dss_10.2.4 = Account lockout failures -->
    <!-- pci_dss_10.2.5 = Use of authentication mechanisms -->
    <!-- gpg13_7.1 = User activity is logged -->
    <group>authentication_failures,brute_force,pci_dss_10.2.4,pci_dss_10.2.5,gpg13_7.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100002 — Successful Login After Brute Force (Critical Escalation)
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         This is a CORRELATION rule. It looks for a successful SSH login
         (built-in rule 5715) occurring from the SAME source IP that
         already triggered rule 100001 (brute force) within 120 seconds.
         This is the "brute force succeeded" detector — it fires at level
         15 (maximum) because this is a confirmed or near-confirmed compromise.

       WHY THIS APPROACH:
         Many SOCs only alert on failures. This rule correlates FAILURE+SUCCESS
         from the same IP to detect the moment a brute force actually works.
         Level 15 ensures this fires PagerDuty/on-call escalation immediately.

       IMPORTANT NOTES:
         - <if_matched_sid> points to 100001 (our custom rule), not 5760
         - <if_sid>5715 means "AND also the current event is a successful login"
         - <same_source_ip> ensures it's the SAME attacker who bruted, not a
           coincidental legit login from a different IP

       TUNING GUIDE:
         timeframe="120": 2 minutes between brute force and success detection.
         Increase to 300 if attackers are pacing their attacks slowly.
         This rule has very low false positive rates — almost any fire is real.

       RESPONSE: IMMEDIATE — do not wait for analyst review
                 Lock account: sudo passwd -l <user>
                 Kill sessions: sudo pkill -u <user>
                 Escalate to Critical in TheHive
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100002" level="15" timeframe="120">

    <!-- Correlation: must have seen brute force from same IP recently -->
    <if_matched_sid>100001</if_matched_sid>
    <same_source_ip />

    <!-- The current event must ALSO be a successful login (rule 5715) -->
    <if_sid>5715</if_sid>   <!-- sshd: authentication success -->

    <description>CRITICAL: Successful SSH login from $(srcip) after brute force — possible compromise</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1110.001</id>   <!-- Brute Force: Password Guessing (success) -->
      <id>T1078</id>        <!-- Valid Accounts (attacker now has valid creds) -->
    </mitre>

    <group>authentication_success,brute_force,pci_dss_10.2.4,pci_dss_10.2.5</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100003 — LSASS Memory Access (Credential Dumping)
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Matches Sysmon Event ID 10 (ProcessAccess) where the TARGET of the
         memory access operation is lsass.exe. The Windows Local Security
         Authority Subsystem Service stores credentials in memory including
         NTLM hashes and Kerberos tickets — it is the #1 target for
         credential dumpers: Mimikatz, ProcDump, SharpDump, Credential
         Guard bypass tools.

       FIELD BREAKDOWN:
         win.system.eventID = "10"   : Sysmon EID 10 = ProcessAccess event
         win.eventdata.targetImage   : The process being READ from (lsass.exe)
         type="pcre2"                : Use Perl-Compatible Regular Expressions
         (?i)                        : Case-insensitive match
         lsass\.exe$                 : Matches the filename, anchored to end
                                       (prevents "notlsass.exe" from matching)

       WHY NOT CHECK sourceImage (the attacker process)?
         Attackers rename their tools constantly. Matching the TARGET (lsass.exe)
         is more reliable than matching the source process name. Any process
         reading lsass.exe memory is suspicious — Windows itself has very few
         legitimate reasons to do this (WER, certain AV products).

       REDUCING FALSE POSITIVES:
         Known false positive sources:
           - Windows Error Reporting (WerFault.exe) accessing lsass after crash
           - Some AV/EDR products that monitor LSASS
           - Microsoft Defender credential harvesting protection
         To exclude these, add:
           <field name="win.eventdata.sourceImage" negate="yes" type="pcre2">
             (?i)(WerFault|MsMpEng|SenseIR|CylanceSvc)\.exe$
           </field>

       SYSMON CONFIGURATION REQUIRED:
         Your Sysmon config must have ProcessAccess logging enabled with
         lsass.exe as a target. Add to sysmonconfig.xml:
           <ProcessAccess onmatch="include">
             <TargetImage condition="is">C:\Windows\system32\lsass.exe</TargetImage>
           </ProcessAccess>

       RESPONSE: Isolate host immediately
                 Assume all credentials on host are compromised
                 Rotate passwords for all accounts used on this system
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100003" level="14">

    <!-- Only process Windows events -->
    <if_group>windows</if_group>

    <!-- Sysmon Event ID 10 = ProcessAccess -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID">^10$</field>

    <!-- Target process must be lsass.exe (case-insensitive, end-anchored) -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.targetImage" type="pcre2">(?i)lsass\.exe$</field>

    <!-- Dynamic substitution: shows WHICH process accessed LSASS in the alert -->
    <description>Credential dumping attempt: process $(win.eventdata.sourceImage) accessed LSASS memory on $(hostname)</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1003.001</id>   <!-- OS Credential Dumping: LSASS Memory -->
    </mitre>

    <group>credential_dumping,attack,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100004 — PsExec Lateral Movement Detection
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Detects the use of PsExec (and similar tools) for lateral movement.
         PsExec works by:
           1. Copying PSEXESVC.exe to the target's ADMIN$ share
           2. Creating a service named PSEXESVC via the Service Control Manager
           3. Executing commands via that service

         This rule matches EITHER:
           - Sysmon EID 1 (Process Create) where image path contains psexec
           - Windows Security EID 7045 (New Service Installed) for PSEXESVC

       MULTI-FIELD MATCHING:
         The pipe "|" in field name="win.eventdata.image|win.eventdata.serviceName"
         means: check EITHER of these fields. This is a Wazuh feature for
         OR-matching across multiple decoded fields.

       CATCHING RENAMED PSEXEC:
         The regex catches: psexec, psexesvc, paexec (a PsExec clone).
         It does NOT catch completely renamed variants — for those, use
         Sysmon's hash-based matching with a blocklist of known PsExec hashes.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         If your environment legitimately uses PsExec for admin tasks:
           1. Move this rule to level 8 (Medium) instead of 13
           2. Add a <field name="win.eventdata.user" negate="yes"> exclusion
              for known admin accounts that legitimately use PsExec
           3. Create a separate rule at level 13 for PsExec by non-admin accounts

       RESPONSE: Identify the source host (who executed PsExec)
                 Identify the destination host (where PSEXESVC appeared)
                 Use lateral-movement-playbook.md
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100004" level="13">

    <if_group>windows</if_group>

    <!-- Match process creation (EID 1) OR new service installed (EID 7045) -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID">^1$|^7045$</field>

    <!-- Either the image/binary name OR the service name contains PsExec variants -->
    <!-- | = OR across multiple fields -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.image|win.eventdata.serviceName" type="pcre2">(?i)(psexec|psexesvc|paexec)</field>

    <description>Lateral movement via PsExec detected: $(win.eventdata.image) on $(hostname) — possible remote execution</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1021.002</id>   <!-- Remote Services: SMB/Windows Admin Shares -->
      <id>T1570</id>        <!-- Lateral Tool Transfer -->
    </mitre>

    <group>lateral_movement,attack,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100005 — Suspicious PowerShell Execution
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Matches PowerShell process creation events (from either Sysmon EID 1
         or Windows Security EID 4688) where the command line contains flags
         and patterns overwhelmingly associated with malicious use:

         PATTERNS DETECTED:
           -enc / -EncodedCommand  : Base64-encoded payload (obfuscation)
           -ep bypass              : Bypass execution policy restrictions
           -ExecutionPolicy Bypass : Same as above, long form
           IEX / Invoke-Expression : Execute strings as code (download cradles)
           Net.WebClient           : .NET HTTP client (download tools)
           DownloadString          : Downloads and executes from URL
           DownloadFile            : Downloads file from URL
           FromBase64String        : Decodes base64 payload
           -nop / -NonInteractive  : Suppress user interaction (automation)
           -WindowStyle Hidden     : Hide the PowerShell window (stealth)
           WebRequest / Invoke-WebRequest: HTTP downloads

       WHY TWO EVENT ID OPTIONS:
         EID 1 (Sysmon): Captures command line BEFORE execution — more reliable
         EID 4688 (Security): Available even without Sysmon — fallback detection
         The "|" in eventID field matches either.

       FIELD NAME PIPE TRICK:
         win.eventdata.commandLine|win.eventdata.processCommandLine
         These are different field names used by Sysmon vs Security logs.
         Checking both ensures coverage regardless of log source.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         High false positive sources:
           - Microsoft SCCM / Intune management scripts (often use -EncodedCommand)
           - Ansible WinRM connections (uses encoded commands)
           - Some backup software
         To exclude known-good sources:
           <field name="win.eventdata.parentImage" negate="yes" type="pcre2">
             (?i)(CCMExec|sccm|ansible|chef|puppet)
           </field>

       RESPONSE: Decode the base64 payload (if present):
                 [System.Text.Encoding]::UTF8.GetString([Convert]::FromBase64String('<payload>'))
                 Check if URL is malicious via VirusTotal
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100005" level="12">

    <if_group>windows</if_group>

    <!-- Match either Sysmon process create OR Security process create -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID">^1$|^4688$</field>

    <!-- The process being created must be PowerShell -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.image|win.eventdata.newProcessName" type="pcre2">(?i)powershell(\.exe)?$</field>

    <!-- The command line must contain suspicious flags/patterns -->
    <!-- This long regex catches the most common malicious PS patterns -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.commandLine|win.eventdata.processCommandLine" type="pcre2">(?i)(-enc|-EncodedCommand|-ep bypass|-ExecutionPolicy\s+Bypass|IEX|Invoke-Expression|Net\.WebClient|DownloadString|DownloadFile|FromBase64String|-nop|-NonInteractive|-WindowStyle\s+[Hh]idden|WebRequest|Invoke-WebRequest)</field>

    <description>Suspicious PowerShell execution on $(hostname): encoded/download/bypass flags detected — $(win.eventdata.commandLine)</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1059.001</id>   <!-- Command and Scripting Interpreter: PowerShell -->
    </mitre>

    <group>attack,powershell,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100006 — Ransomware Behaviour: Mass File Encryption
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Uses two mechanisms together:
           1. frequency="20" timeframe="30": fires only after 20 syscheck
              (File Integrity Monitoring) events in 30 seconds — indicating
              mass file modification, which is the hallmark of ransomware
           2. Filename extension regex: the new file path must end with a
              known ransomware extension to avoid false positives from
              legitimate software that modifies many files quickly (backup
              tools, compilers, package managers)

       THE FREQUENCY + SYSCHECK APPROACH:
         <if_matched_group>syscheck</if_matched_group> with frequency="20"
         means: "fire when ANY 20 syscheck events matching this rule have
         occurred in 30 seconds." This is a volume-based detection — it
         catches ransomware even if it uses novel file extensions, as long as
         the extension matches the known list.

       THE EXTENSION LIST:
         200+ known ransomware family extensions including:
           WannaCry: .wncry .wcry
           Locky: .locky .zepto
           Cerber: .cerber
           REvil/Sodinokibi: .revil
           Conti: .conti
           Ryuk: .ryuk
           STOP/Djvu: .djvu .stop
         Update this list as new families emerge.

       WHY LEVEL 15:
         Ransomware is the highest-impact threat to availability. Every second
         of delay costs more encrypted files. Level 15 triggers the maximum
         alert priority in any connected notification system.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         If you get false positives from backup software creating .encrypted
         staging files, add a path exclusion:
           <field name="syscheck.path" negate="yes" type="pcre2">
             (?i)(backup|archive|vault)
           </field>
         Increase frequency to 50 if your environment has software that
         legitimately renames many files quickly.

       RESPONSE: IMMEDIATE HOST ISOLATION — every second matters
                 Do NOT reboot (destroys memory evidence)
                 Check if backups are intact before remediation
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100006" level="15" frequency="20" timeframe="30">

    <!-- Parent group: fires when syscheck (FIM) events are matching -->
    <if_matched_group>syscheck</if_matched_group>

    <!-- The file path must end with a known ransomware extension -->
    <!-- (?i) = case insensitive, $ = end of string anchor -->
    <field name="syscheck.path" type="pcre2">(?i)\.(locked|encrypted|enc|crypt|crypto|vault|rrr|locky|zepto|cerber|thor|aaa|abc|xyz|crypted|cryptowall|ransom|pay|crypz|micro|cryptolocker|wncry|wcry|wanacry|satan|petya|notpetya|globe|jaff|dharma|phobos|stop|djvu|sodinokibi|revil|maze|egregor|conti|ryuk|darkside)$</field>

    <description>RANSOMWARE BEHAVIOR: Mass file encryption detected on $(hostname) — $(syscheck.path) — ISOLATE IMMEDIATELY</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1486</id>   <!-- Data Encrypted for Impact -->
    </mitre>

    <group>ransomware,attack,critical,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100007 — Registry Run Key Persistence
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Detects writes to the Windows autorun registry keys via Sysmon
         Event ID 13 (RegistryValueSet). These keys cause arbitrary programs
         to execute at user login or system boot — the most common persistence
         mechanism used by malware, RATs, and APTs.

       REGISTRY PATHS MONITORED:
         HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run
           → Runs for ALL users at login
         HKLM\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce
           → Runs ONCE for all users (used by installers AND malware)
         HKLM\Software\Wow6432Node\...\Run
           → 32-bit autorun on 64-bit Windows
         HKLM\System\CurrentControlSet\Services
           → Service creation (used by rootkits and malicious drivers)
         HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Winlogon
           → Winlogon notification (used for DLL injection persistence)
         HKCU\...\Run
           → Per-user autorun (lower privilege, but very commonly abused)

       SYSMON EVENT ID 13:
         EID 13 = RegistryValueSet — fires when a registry value is written.
         The field win.eventdata.targetObject contains the full registry path.
         win.eventdata.image contains the process that made the write.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         Common legitimate writers to these keys:
           - Software installers (msiexec.exe, setup.exe)
           - Windows Update
           - OneDrive, Teams, Zoom auto-updaters
         To reduce noise from known-good apps:
           <field name="win.eventdata.image" negate="yes" type="pcre2">
             (?i)(msiexec|OneDriveSetup|Teams|Zoom|MicrosoftEdge)
           </field>
         But be careful — attackers masquerade as legitimate process names.

       RESPONSE: Check what value was written to the key
                 Investigate the process that wrote it
                 Correlate with rule 100005 (suspicious PowerShell)
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100007" level="12">

    <if_group>windows</if_group>

    <!-- EID 13 = Sysmon RegistryValueSet event -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID">^13$</field>

    <!-- The registry key path must be one of the persistence locations -->
    <!-- (?i) = case-insensitive, handles HKLM vs hklm, etc. -->
    <!-- Note: backslashes are doubled in XML (\ becomes \\) -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.targetObject" type="pcre2">(?i)\\(HKLM|HKCU|HKU|HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE|HKEY_CURRENT_USER)\\(Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run|Software\\Wow6432Node\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run|System\\CurrentControlSet\\Services|SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Winlogon)</field>

    <description>Persistence via registry Run key: $(win.eventdata.targetObject) modified by $(win.eventdata.image) on $(hostname)</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1547.001</id>   <!-- Boot or Logon Autostart Execution: Registry Run Keys -->
    </mitre>

    <group>persistence,attack,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100008 — Suspicious Scheduled Task Creation
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Detects creation of scheduled tasks with suspicious characteristics
         using two detection paths:
           Path A: Windows Security EID 4698 (A scheduled task was created)
                   combined with a regex check on the task content/command
           Path B: Sysmon EID 1 (Process Create) where schtasks.exe is
                   called with suspicious arguments

       THE SUSPICIOUS ARGUMENT PATTERNS:
         /sc onstart      → Runs at system startup (persistence)
         /sc onlogon      → Runs at every user login (persistence)
         /ru system       → Runs as SYSTEM (privilege escalation)
         /tr ...\temp\    → Binary in temp directory (malware staging)
         /tr ...\appdata\ → Binary in AppData (user-writable, malware staging)
         powershell       → Task runs PowerShell (combine with rule 100005)
         cmd.exe /c ...\temp → CMD running something from temp
         base64/encoded   → Encoded payload in task action

       WHY BOTH EID 4698 AND EID 1:
         4698 gives you the task XML content — better for detecting malicious
         task configurations. EID 1 gives you the schtasks.exe command line —
         better for catching creation via command line tools.
         Matching either ensures maximum coverage.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         Legitimate scheduled tasks in enterprises are common. Reduce noise by:
           1. Excluding known software: SCCM, Intune, backup agents
           2. Only alerting on /ru system + non-standard directories combo
           3. Creating a whitelist of known-good task names in a CDB list

       RESPONSE: Review full task definition in Task Scheduler
                 Check binary the task executes (hash it)
                 Determine if task was created by a legitimate admin
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100008" level="12">

    <if_group>windows</if_group>

    <!-- Match Security EID 4698 (task created) OR Sysmon EID 1 (process create) -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID">^4698$|^1$</field>

    <!-- Task name or command line must contain suspicious indicators -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.taskName|win.eventdata.commandLine" type="pcre2">(?i)(schtasks|taskschd).*(/sc\s+onstart|/sc\s+onlogon|/ru\s+system|/tr\s+.*\\(temp|tmp|appdata|programdata)\\|powershell|cmd\.exe\s+/c\s+.*\\(temp|tmp)|\\AppData\\|base64|encoded)</field>

    <description>Suspicious scheduled task created on $(hostname): $(win.eventdata.taskName) — check for persistence mechanism</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1053.005</id>   <!-- Scheduled Task/Job: Scheduled Task -->
    </mitre>

    <group>persistence,attack,pci_dss_10.6.1</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100009 — Outbound Connection to Suspicious Ports (Possible C2)
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Monitors Sysmon EID 3 (NetworkConnect) events for outbound connections
         to port numbers that are overwhelmingly associated with:
           - Metasploit reverse shells (4444, 4445)
           - Hacker culture / memes (1337, 31337 = "leet")
           - Common C2 frameworks (8888, 9999)
           - IRC (6666–6669) — used by older botnets
           - SOCKS proxies (1080, 3128)
           - Common C2 over HTTP-like ports (8080, 8443, 9090)

       LIMITATIONS AND UPGRADE PATH:
         This rule uses a hardcoded port list — a simplification for the lab.
         In production, replace this with:
           1. A Wazuh CDB (Constant Database) list of known-bad IPs from
              threat intel feeds (Emerging Threats, AlienVault OTX, etc.)
           2. Anomaly-based detection on ports that are unusual for THIS
              specific endpoint (requires baseline period)
           3. DNS-based detection for C2 domain generation algorithms (DGA)

       WHY THESE SPECIFIC PORTS:
         Port 4444: Default Metasploit meterpreter listener
         Port 1337: "Leet" — used in many CTF/red team tools as default
         Port 31337: "Elite" — classic backdoor/netcat listen port
         Port 8888/9999: Common custom C2 framework defaults
         Port 6666-6669: IRC — botnet C2 communication channel
         Port 1080: SOCKS proxy — often used for tunneling C2 traffic

       TUNING GUIDE:
         Remove ports that your environment legitimately uses. For example:
           - Port 8080 is used by many web apps (remove if you have dev servers)
           - Port 3128 is Squid proxy (remove if you use Squid)
         Add ports specific to tools used in your threat model.

       UPGRADE TO CDB LIST (recommended for production):
         Create /var/ossec/etc/lists/malicious-ips.txt
         Add rule: <match_field name="win.eventdata.destinationIp">
                     <list field="win.eventdata.destinationIp" lookup="match_key">
                       etc/lists/malicious-ips
                     </list>
                   </match_field>

       RESPONSE: Check if connection succeeded or was blocked
                 Identify the process that made the connection
                 Isolate if confirmed C2 communication
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100009" level="10">

    <if_group>windows,linux</if_group>

    <!-- Sysmon EID 3 = NetworkConnect -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID|data.eventid">^3$</field>

    <!-- Destination port must be one of the suspicious C2 ports -->
    <!-- ^ and $ anchors prevent partial matches (e.g. port 44444 won't match 4444) -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.destinationPort|data.dstport" type="pcre2">^(4444|4445|1337|31337|8888|9999|6666|6667|6668|6669|1080|3128|8080|8443|8888|9090)$</field>

    <description>Suspicious outbound connection: $(win.eventdata.image) connecting to $(win.eventdata.destinationIp):$(win.eventdata.destinationPort) — possible C2 or proxy</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1071</id>    <!-- Application Layer Protocol (C2 communication) -->
      <id>T1041</id>    <!-- Exfiltration Over C2 Channel -->
    </mitre>

    <group>network,c2,attack,pci_dss_1.3.4</group>

  </rule>


  <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       RULE 100010 — Large File Transfer / Data Exfiltration Attempt
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

       WHAT IT DOES:
         Detects command-line usage of common data transfer tools (curl, wget,
         scp, rsync, netcat, certutil) with flags indicating large transfers
         or piping to network destinations. These patterns are strongly
         associated with data exfiltration.

       TOOLS MONITORED AND WHY:
         curl      : Most versatile HTTP exfil tool — supports PUT/POST of files
         wget      : HTTP download/upload — less common for exfil but possible
         scp       : SSH copy — legitimate admin tool, suspicious off-hours
         rsync     : Sync large directories — attacker favourite for exfil
         nc/ncat   : Raw TCP streams — simplest exfil method possible
         certutil  : Windows LOLBin — base64 encodes/decodes files, used for exfil
         bitsadmin : Windows LOLBin — Background Intelligent Transfer Service

       FLAG PATTERNS:
         -T <largenum>      : curl upload with large size (>10000 bytes)
         -b <largenum>      : byte range
         --data-binary      : Sends raw binary data (file upload)
         | nc/curl/wget     : Pipes output directly to network (classic exfil)
         --limit-rate [MG]  : Throttled transfer (attackers evade rate limits)

       LIMITATIONS:
         This rule catches OBVIOUS exfiltration using standard tools.
         Sophisticated attackers will:
           - Use encrypted channels (HTTPS) — needs SSL inspection
           - Use cloud storage APIs (Google Drive, Dropbox, OneDrive)
           - Use DNS tunneling — needs DNS query monitoring
           - Use small, slow transfers to avoid volume detection
         This rule is layer 1 of a multi-layer exfil detection strategy.

       TUNING GUIDE:
         If your admins legitimately use rsync for backups:
           Add exclusion for the backup service account user
           Add exclusion for known-good destination IPs (backup server)
         If developers use curl heavily:
           Scope this rule to servers only (agent group filter)

       RESPONSE: Capture the full command line as evidence
                 Check destination IP/domain via threat intel
                 Estimate data volume transferred
                 Preserve network logs for forensics
       ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
  <rule id="100010" level="12">

    <if_group>windows,linux</if_group>

    <!-- Match network connection events OR process creation events -->
    <field name="win.system.eventID|data.eventid">^3$|^1$</field>

    <!-- Command line or image must contain data transfer tool + large-transfer flag -->
    <!-- This long regex catches the most common exfil command patterns -->
    <field name="win.eventdata.commandLine|data.command|win.eventdata.image" type="pcre2">(?i)(curl|wget|scp|rsync|ftp|sftp|nc|ncat|netcat|certutil|bitsadmin).*((-T\s+[1-9]\d{4,})|(-b\s+[1-9]\d{4,})|(--limit-rate\s+[0-9]+[MG])|(--data-binary)|(\|\s*(nc|ncat|netcat|curl|wget)))</field>

    <description>Potential data exfiltration on $(hostname): large transfer tool detected — $(win.eventdata.commandLine) to $(win.eventdata.destinationIp)</description>

    <mitre>
      <id>T1048</id>   <!-- Exfiltration Over Alternative Protocol -->
      <id>T1030</id>   <!-- Data Transfer Size Limits -->
    </mitre>

    <group>exfiltration,attack,pci_dss_4.1</group>

  </rule>

</group>
